The Problem

Objective: Build a model to predict the risk of diabetes progression one year after baseline. This prediction will serve as a screening tool for physicians to identify at-risk patients.

Dependent Variable: target - Disease progression one year after baseline.
Independent Variables: 10 baseline variables such as age, sex, body mass index (BMI), average blood pressure, and six blood serum measurements.

In[11]:
results = []

def generate_model(X, y, degree, X_val=None, y_val=None):
    model = LinearRegression()
        
    if degree != 0: 
        poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree, include_bias=False)
    else:
        poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree, include_bias=True)
        
    X_train_poly = poly_features.fit_transform(X)
    model.fit(X_train_poly, y)
    X_val_poly = poly_features.transform(X_val)

    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val_poly)

    mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_val - y_val_pred) / y_val)) * 100
    r2 = r2_score(y_val, y_val_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_val_pred)
    results.append((degree, r2, mae, mape))
    
    return model

Conclusion

Model performance:

  • The degree 2 polynomial regression model produced on the test set an R of 0.449, indicating that almost 45% of the variance in disease progression was explained by BMI.
  • This can be interpreted from the value of MAE ~ 0.54; in other words, the model's predictions are off on average by 0.54 units of disease progression.
  • As shown, the ~101.07% MAPE indicates that, on average, the predictions are about 100% off from the actual values.

Model Limitations:

  • Univariate Analysis: Using only BMI overlooks other potentially significant predictors of diabetes progression. This may limit the model's accuracy and generalizability.
  • Overfitting Risk: Higher-degree polynomials may overfit the training data, reducing the model's performance on unseen data.

Where the Model Fails:

  • External Validity: The model's performance is limited to the specific dataset and may not generalize well to different populations or settings.
  • Feature Interaction: The model does not account for interactions between BMI and other features, potentially missing important predictive relationships.

Conclusion

Model Performances:

  • Degree 3 Polynomial: It yielded an R of approximately 0.47 on the test set. That means a slight improvement over the univariate model when taking into consideration all features.
  • Decision Trees: Both models gave decent performances, falling short of the performance from polynomial regression models.
  • kNN Models: Were at the bottom of the list concerning the performance of previous models that used polynomials and decision trees.

Limitations of Models:

  • Polynomial Regression: Complex relationships among features might be difficult for even this model to catch once higher-order polynomial terms are reached.
  • Overfitting Risk: Higher-degree polynomials are very prone to overfitting on the training data; using cross-validation may help weaken this effect.
  • Decision Trees: Very sensitive to parameter settings and most probably will not generalize well if not tuned properly. k-NN models: Their performance is heavily dependent on the chosen value of 'k' and feature scaling. Recommendations:
